<section xml:id="lesson-10">
  <title>Lesson 10</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Determine whether a function is a polynomial.</li>
      <li>Write polynomials in standard form.</li>
      <li>Identify the degree, leading term, and constant of a polynomial.</li>
      <li>Analyze polynomial graphs to determine degree and end behavior.</li>
      <li>Determine zeros, multiplicities, and behavior at zeros.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="l10-polynomial-identification">
    <title>Identifying Polynomial Functions</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l10-ex1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine whether each of the following functions is a polynomial.
          If it is a polynomial, write it in standard form and list the degree,
          leading term, and constant. If it is not a polynomial, explain why.
        </p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>f(x)=\frac{x}{2}-x^2+\sqrt{7}+x^7+x^4</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x)=-6x^5+2\sqrt{x}</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x)=5x^2+\frac{4}{x^2+x}+x^5</m></li>
          <li><m>(7x-3)(x^2-2x+7)</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l10-polynomial-characteristics">
    <title>Polynomial Characteristics from Graphs</title>

    <remark>
      <p>
        For the following exercises, use the image of a polynomial to answer
        the questions that follow.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <exercise xml:id="l10-ex2">
      <statement>
        <figure>
          <caption>Polynomial graph for analysis</caption>
          <image source="../figures/polychar1-review.png">
            <description><p>Graph of a polynomial used to determine degree parity, leading coefficient sign, constant sign, and minimum degree.</p></description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Is the degree of the polynomial even or odd?
            even or odd
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the leading coefficient positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the constant positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>What is the minimum degree?</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="l10-ex3">
      <statement>
        <figure>
          <caption>Polynomial graph for analysis</caption>
          <image source="../figures/polychar2-review.png">
            <description><p>Graph of a polynomial used to determine degree parity, leading coefficient sign, constant sign, and minimum degree.</p></description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Is the degree of the polynomial even or odd?
            even or odd
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the leading coefficient positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the constant positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>What is the minimum degree?</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="l10-ex4">
      <statement>
        <figure>
          <caption>Polynomial graph for analysis</caption>
          <image source="../figures/polychar3-review.png">
            <description><p>Graph of a polynomial used to determine degree parity, leading coefficient sign, constant sign, and minimum degree.</p></description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Is the degree of the polynomial even or odd?
            even or odd
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the leading coefficient positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>
            Is the constant positive or negative?
            positive or negative
          </li>
          <li>What is the minimum degree?</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l10-zeros-multiplicity">
    <title>Zeros, Multiplicity, and Graph Behavior</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l10-ex5">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For <m>f(x)=x(x+2)(x-5)^4</m>:
        </p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            Determine the zeros, give the multiplicity, and determine whether
            the function crosses or touches the <m>x</m>-axis at each zero.
          </li>
          <li>Determine the end behavior of the graph of <m>f(x)</m>.</li>
          <li>
            Determine where the function is above the <m>x</m>-axis and where
            the function is below the <m>x</m>-axis.
          </li>
          <li>Determine the <m>y</m>-intercept.</li>
          <li>Graph the function.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

</section>